OceanoPeixesTubaroes

Class Ocean

  • java.lang.Object
    • OceanoPeixesTubaroes.Ocean

  • public class Ocean
extends java.lang.Object
    The Ocean class defines an object that models an ocean full of sharks and fish. Descriptions of the methods you must implement appear below. They include a constructor of the form public Ocean(int i, int j, int starveTime); that creates an empty ocean having width i and height j, in which sharks starve after starveTime timesteps. See the README file accompanying this project for additional details.

      • addShark

        public void addShark(int x,
            int y)
        addShark() (with two parameters) places a newborn shark in cell (x, y) if the cell is empty. A "newborn" shark is equivalent to a shark that has just eaten. If the cell is already occupied, leave the cell as it is.
        Parameters:
        x - is the x-coordinate of the cell to place a shark in.
        y - is the y-coordinate of the cell to place a shark in.

      • addShark

        public void addShark(int x,
            int y,
            int feeding)
        addShark() (with three parameters) places a shark in cell (x, y) if the cell is empty. The shark's hunger is represented by the third parameter. If the cell is already occupied, leave the cell as it is. You will need this method to help convert run-length encodings to Oceans.
        Parameters:
        x - is the x-coordinate of the cell to place a shark in.
        y - is the y-coordinate of the cell to place a shark in.
        feeding - is an integer that indicates the shark's hunger. You may encode it any way you want; for instance, "feeding" may be the last timestep the shark was fed, or the amount of time that has passed since the shark was last fed, or the amount of time left before the shark will starve. It's up to you, but be consistent.

      • sharkFeeding

        public int sharkFeeding(int x,
               int y)
        sharkFeeding() returns an integer that indicates the hunger of the shark in cell (x, y), using the same "feeding" representation as the parameter to addShark() described above. If cell (x, y) does not contain a shark, then its return value is undefined--that is, anything you want. Normally, this method should not be called if cell (x, y) does not contain a shark. You will need this method to help convert Oceans to run-length encodings.
        Parameters:
        x - is the x-coordinate of the cell whose contents are queried.
        y - is the y-coordinate of the cell whose contents are queried.
        Returns:
